div.p:
"Take thy son, thine only son Isaac."Genesis 22:2—God here calls Isaac the only son of Abraham. Why does he so, when Ishmael was alive, and already had God's promise to become the father of a numerous nation? 1st, Because ISaac was the only son of Abraham, by Sarah his wife; 2dly, Because he was the child of God's promise, and therefore the only one who could claim God's covenant; for, as St.Paul says, the promise of God was unto Abraham and his seed, not unto seeds. 3dly, The term only is also frequently used to express a particular degree of affection;



    as if God had said, Thy son Isaac, thy only blessing, thy only hope, the prop of thy present life, declining as it is; the pledge of living, when the grave has closed over thee, in the hearts of a numerous and grateful posterity. This is more strongly touched upon in the succeeding words, "whom thou lovest"Genesis 22:2—whom he might well indeed love as the last gift of Heaven, the reward of his faith, and hope, and charity, the very seal of a covenant so solemnly ratified by God himself. This object of almost holy, as well as natural affection, he was to lose, to lose in what appeared the most unreasonable and barbarous manner. He, the father, was to lift the knife against the innocent throat. But where was the sacrifice to take place? Here we meet with another circumstance of minute and mysterious signfication. He was, with all this load of anguish preying on his mind, without daring to seek the consolation of his wife, acting, as it were, with dissimulation towards his household and treachery towards his son; he was to journey to a considerable distance, to a spot which he knew not of—to the land of Moriah, and there be directed by God's hand to a particular mountain. Now the land of Moriah was that which was afterwarads to form the centre and citadel of David's kingdom; it was to be the site of Jerusalem, nay, of the very temple itself. We read, that Solomon began to



    build the house of the Lord at Jerusalem on Mount Moriah, where the Lord appeared unto David his father in the place that David had prepared in the threshing-floor of Ornan, or Araunah, the Jebusite.
